\begin_layout Subsection
Raising Equity Capital
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Looking at the number of businesses in the U.S.
 71% of them are sole proprietorships, but by revenue - 84% are corporations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A business generally starts with the enterpreneurs' money (friends, family
 etc).
 Upon success, a company must seek other sources of capital.
 For private firms the options are:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Angel Investors
\series default
: individual investors who buy equity in small amount (~$200K).
 They enter in the first seed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Venture Capital Firm (VC)
\series default
: A limited partnership which invests in young firms, demanding a substantial
 control (~1/3 of the seats in the board of directors).
 A VC firm won't invest at once, bu rather in rounds.
 They are usually a group of people with a lot of knowledge and connections
 that can (usually) be trusted.
 A successful VC would have ~10% success rate.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Private Equity Firms
\series default
: firms with a lot of money, which invest in order to 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

take out
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 the firm by buying the whole equity (LBO).
 They are larger than VC and more focused on specific firms.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Institutional Investors
\series default
: pension funds, insurance companies, etc.
 They may invest directly, or by becoming limited partners in VCs.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Corporate Investors
\series default
: they might invest not only for the financial return, but for corporate
 strategic objectives (e.g Google, Facebook, etc).
\end_layout

