\begin_layout Subsubsection
Underpricing
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Generally, on the first day after the IPO the price is going up (average
 of 18%).
 First-day returns are usually positive, and in many cases are above 50%.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One of the reasons is asymmetric information.
 Consider, for example, an IPO with 1 million outstanding shares.
 The founder wishes to sell 75% of the equity, there are 1.5 million investors
 with imilted wealth such that each one of them is able to buy only a single
 share.
 The allocation will be determined by the cumulative demand.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the market estimate the value of the firm to be $100M ot $200M with 50%
 probability, the value will be $150M.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In case of symmetric information (all investors have the same information
 regarding the firm's value), every investor is willing to pay $150 per
 share.
 If the firm offers shares at $150, as there are 1.5 million investors competing
 on 750,000 shares - the probability to participate in the IPO is 50%.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In a scenario of asymmetric information (assume 500000 investors know the
 true value of the firm), the issue price cannot be $150.
 If it was $150, the informed investors would participate only if the true
 value was $200M.
 The uninformed investors particiapte as well, which leads to total demand
 of 1.5 million shares, and the probability of participating is again 50%.
 If the true value is $100 million, the informed investors won't participate,
 the total demanl will be 1 million and the probability of participating
 will be 75%.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The expected profit of the uninformed investors is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
0.5\cdot50\%\cdot(200-150)+0.5\cdot75\%\cdot(100-150)=-6.25
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus, on average the uninformed investors lose in the IPO (
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

the winner's curse
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

), and in order to make them participate in the IPO, the firm must set the
 price below $150.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The uninformed investors will participate when the expected profit is 0:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
0.5\cdot50\%\cdot(200-P_{IPO})+0.5\cdot75\%\cdot(100-P_{IPO})=-6.25\Rightarrow P_{IPO}=140
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The informed investors benefit from this phenomena, and the pre-IPO shreholders
 lose from it.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the Israeli market this model indeed exists.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are several reasons for underpricing:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Asymmetric information
\series default
: need to induce the uninformed investors to participate.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Underwriters
\series default
: they benefit from underpricing.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Litigation avoidance
\series default
: firms might get sued for not pricing correctly (someone might find something
 which is not accurate enough).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
The herding phenomena
\series default
: if investors estimate a strong/weak demand, they participate/avoid the
 IPO, which leads to uversubscription/undersubscription.
 Firms try to produce artificial herding.
\end_layout

